<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE BUTCHER: TAKE FOOD COMMERCIALS WITH A GRAIN OF SALT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MERLE ELLIS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As consumers we are being inundated more and more these days with nutritional 
information. It comes at us from every angle, and much of it, I think, indeed 
does have an angle. Much of it comes to us compliments of somebody trying to 
sell us something. 
</P>
<P>
Television commercials for everything from calcium-enriched orange juice to 
polyunsaturated cooking oil try to convince us that their products are really 
the best for us. 
</P>
<P>
If you use product "X," you will be healthier, live longer and more productive 
lives, have lower incidence of heart disease, cancer, diabetes, arthritis, 
hardening of the arteries, sexual impotence. Not only that, if you use product 
"X" in conjunction with "our proven diet plan," "our proven exercise program" 
or in a fat-modified diet including "our oat bran," "natural kiwi fuzz" and our 
special "raspberry dazzle" you can conceivably expect to "live well past your 
normal life expectancy. You have our word on it." 
</P>
<P>
It has, I think, gotten a little out of hand. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Like the Snake Oil Salesman 
</P>
<P>
In my opinion the seller of nutrition today is remarkably similar to the snake 
oil salesman of years gone by. "Right this way ladies and gentlemen, I hold in 
my hand the sure cure for . . . ." Today's society still succumbs to the 
promise for simple cures of any ailment, from the guarantee of quick, near 
miraculous weight loss -- like Oprah's -- to the more subtle promise of a 
dietary cure for diabetes or cancer. In my opinion we, in America, are 
bombarded daily with nutrition information that ranges from simply incorrect to 
blatant fraud. 
</P>
<P>
Grain cereals are beginning to advertise, "Contains no cholesterol." That's 
wonderful. Fits perfectly with "today's active life styles" and all that, but 
the fact is that unless the grains advertised were once made with animal fat 
(which is highly unlikely -- like making orange juice with apples), they never 
did contain cholesterol. So why are they now advertising that they contain "no 
cholesterol?" 
</P>
<P>
Is all of this nutrition information really worth anything to us at all, or is 
it mostly just hype? 
</P>
<P>
I picked up a flyer at the checkout counter of my supermarket the other day as 
I checked out my steaks, tomatoes and canned anchovies. It read: "Nutrition 
Therapy -- Chewable Oat Bran Fiber with apple pectin -- Nutrition Therapy 
chewable Oat Bran Fiber, 500 mg. is processed in a way that concentrates the 
protein, vitamins and minerals found naturally in oats. More importantly, 
chewable oat bran is high in water-soluble fiber, which medical research has 
indicated may be helpful in lowering cholesterol levels when used as part of a 
total dietary program." 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
In Big Red Letters 
</P>
<P>
The words "lowering cholesterol levels" were, of course, in big red letters. 
</P>
<P>
Reading the label and literature on some of our food products is getting to be 
a bit more complicated than reading a legal document. We need a nutritionist 
these days just as we need a lawyer to help us wade through the rhetoric and 
find reality. Finding one, however, is not nearly so easy as finding a lawyer. 
Lawyers are everywhere. There are 31 pages of attorneys listed in the Yellow 
Pages of my phone directory, but only 21 names listed between "nursing homes" 
and "nuts-edible" under the heading "nutritionists" and only two of these have 
"RD" after their name. There were several "Ph.D.s" and "MDs" but those letters 
don't often mean very much when it comes to nutrition. It is very possible to 
be a Doctor of Philosophy, indeed a world-famous brain surgeon and know very 
little about nutrition. 
</P>
<P>
"RD" stands for registered dietitian and indicates that the person after whose 
name the letters appear has met the requirements established by the Commission 
of Dietetic Registration. Those requirements include a bachelor's degree, 
internship or equivalent program, a national examination and continuing 
postgraduate study. When you need sound nutritional advice about dieting, 
weight loss, reducing fat, salt, cholesterol, etc., don't rely on what you see 
on the television or read on the side of cereal boxes; consult a registered 
dietitian. 
</P>
<P>
To find one in your area, try your local county public health department, 
public health nutritionist, hospital dietary department or simply look in the 
phone book Yellow Pages under the heading "Dietitians" (it's between "Diesel 
Fuel" and "Disk Jockeys"). Don't look for "Nutritionists": Anyone can call 
himself a nutritionist. 
</P>
</TEXT>
