<HEADLINE>
<P>
LIBYA AT A GLANCE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Official Name -- Socialist People's Libyan Arab Jamahiriya, or "state of the 
masses." 
</P>
<P>
Population -- 3.9 million. 
</P>
<P>
Official Language -- Arabic. 
</P>
<P>
Ethnic Divisions -- 97% Arab and Berber. 
</P>
<P>
Religion -- 97% Sunni Muslim. 
</P>
<P>
Government -- Officially, a republic governed by a General People's Congress, 
drawn from popularly elected local councils; in fact, a military dictatorship. 
</P>
<P>
Leader -- Col. Moammar Kadafi, military strongman who holds no governmental 
title. 
</P>
<P>
Political Parties -- None. 
</P>
<P>
Political Background -- Under Ottoman Turkish control for four centuries, then 
an Italian colony from 1912 until Allied victory in World War II; an 
independent, generally pro-Western monarchy from 1949 until radical officers 
under Kadafi took power and set up a revolutionary, military-governed regime in 
1969. 
</P>
<P>
Economy -- Largely based on oil, which dominates exports and brought in $4.5 
billion in1986, roughly half the country's total revenue. Other industries: 
agriculture, fishing, food processing. 
</P>
<P>
Capital -- Tripoli. 
</P>
<P>
Area -- 679,358 square miles, somewhat larger than Alaska. 
</P>
<P>
Climate -- Mediterranean along coast, desert in interior. 
</P>
<P>
Sources: The World Factbook, 1988; Political Handbook of the World, 1988 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Map, Libya ; Drawing, Kadafi 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
