<HEADLINE>
<P>
FACTORY ORDERS ADVANCE 0.3% IN NOVEMBER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
New orders received by American factories, a key indicator of economic 
activity, increased a modest 0.3% in November after a strong 2% jump in 
October, the Commerce Department said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
But economists said the nation's industrial sector was stronger than shown by 
the November orders, which rose despite a sharp drop in orders for military 
hardware, such as tanks and missiles, that fluctuate widely from month to 
month. 
</P>
<P>
Non-defense orders rose a more robust 1.1%, following a 0.6% October gain, the 
department said. 
</P>
<P>
Total orders in November were a seasonally adjusted $227.73 billion, up 8.7% 
from a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
'Looks Healthy' 
</P>
<P>
The biggest order increase in November was for electrical machinery, 
particularly defense communications equipment, while the largest decline was in 
orders for transportation equipment other than commercial aircraft, the 
department said. 
</P>
<P>
"The industrial sector still looks very healthy," said economist David Wyss of 
Data Resources Inc. in Lexington, Mass. 
</P>
<P>
American manufacturers, who have been capitalizing on booming export sales and 
business spending on new equipment, also are recapturing domestic sales from 
foreign companies in chemicals, textiles and primary metals, Wyss said. 
</P>
<P>
A vibrant manufacturing sector will lead the economy through its continuing 
expansion, now in its seventh year, but with less vigor than in 1988, 
economists said. 
</P>
<P>
In one sign of slowing, the index of leading indicators, the government's main 
barometer of future economic activity, registered a 0.2% decline in November, 
the department reported last week. 
</P>
<P>
While economists expect grh in exports and capital spending to slow in 1989, 
there has been little evidence so far that the industrial sector is slowing, 
economists said. 
</P>
<P>
"We're not getting any reports from manufacturers that orders slowed 
significantly in either November or December," said Jerry Jasinowski, chief 
economist for the National Assn. of Manufacturers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Chart, FACTORY ORDERS, Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
