<HEADLINE>
<P>
STOCKS' GAIN BEST SINCE OCTOBER; DOW UP 33.04 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A late burst of program trading, coupled with a sharp rise in the dollar, 
combined Wednesday to give Wall Street stocks their biggest one-day advance in 
more than two months. 
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones index of 30 industrials, down 23.93 on Tuesday, climbed 33.04 to 
2,177.68. 
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered declines by more than 3 to 1 in New York Stock 
Exchange trading, with Big Board volume rising to 149.70 million shares, up 
from 128.50 million Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
"It's a good, broad, impressive rally," one trader said. "I think it's got some 
sustainability to it." 
</P>
<P>
The Dow's rise was the largest since Oct. 20, when it gained 44 points, and 
leaves the index just a few points below its post-crash high of 2,183.50. 
</P>
<P>
Stock analysts attributed the market's strength to a sharp rise in the dollar, 
which added nearly 2 pfennigs against the West German mark on news that U.S. 
Navy jets shot down two Libyan fighters over the Mediterranean Sea. 
</P>
<P>
"We had very strong buy programs kicking in," said Jack Barbanel, senior vice 
president at Gruntal &amp; Co. Traders said futures-linked buying helped the 
Dow double its early gains in the last hour of the session. 
</P>
<P>
An early rise in bond prices also helped the stock market, as did a 28-cent 
drop in the price of U.S. crude oil to $17.08 a barrel. 
</P>
<P>
In foreign trading, the Tokyo stock market started off the new year with a bang 
on Wednesday, climbing to a record close. The 225-share Nikkei index ended an 
abbreviated half-day session up 84.66 at 30,243.66. 
</P>
<P>
London shares ended near the day's highs, boosted by Wall Street's early 
advance and a stronger dollar. The Financial Times index closed up 10.2 at 
1,793 after a 10.3-point drop Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
CREDIT 
</P>
<P>
Bond prices were mixed Wednesday, reacting favorably to a firmer dollar but 
anticipating that Friday's unemployment report might show a big increase in 
jobs, boosting inflation fears. 
</P>
<P>
The Treasury's 30-year bond fell 1/16th of a point, or 62.5 cents per $1,000 
face amount, while its yield closed at 9.08%, unchanged from late Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
Jay Goldinger, of the investment banking firm Capital Insight Inc. in Beverly 
Hills, said the bond market was anticipating Friday's release of federal 
jobless figures for December. 
</P>
<P>
The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between banks, traded 
at 9.125%, down from 9.625% late Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
COMMODITIES 
</P>
<P>
Prices of copper futures rose sharply on the New York Commodity Exchange on 
supply worries rekindled by the apparent bombing of three locomotives in Peru 
and a decline in the exchange's warehouse stocks of copper. 
</P>
<P>
On other markets, precious metals futures retreated, grain and soybean futures 
surged, cattle futures rose while pork futures fell and stock index futures 
advanced. 
</P>
<P>
Copper settled 3.1 to 6.3 cents higher, with the spot contract at $1.58 a pound 
and the more actively traded contract for delivery in March at $1.426 a pound. 
</P>
<P>
The bombing of the locomotives in Peru, the world's sixth-largest copper 
producer, served to remind traders that the settlement last month of a 57-day 
Peruvian miners strike did not defuse the country's internal political tensions 
or the potential for disruptions in the copper pipeline. 
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Commodity Exchange reported a 301-ton decline in its warehouse 
stocks of copper to 7,964 tons. It was the first daily decline after more than 
a week of steady or rising supplies, indicating that copper consumers have 
returned to the marketplace after a holiday break. 
</P>
<P>
Precious metals prices fell on the Comex in response to the dollar's strength, 
which was in turn a reaction to the U.S. downing of two Libyan fighter planes 
off the Libyan coast, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
Tables begin on Page 6. 
</P>
</TEXT>
