<HEADLINE>
<P>
IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
REDS REHIRE BRISTOL -- AS BASE COACH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times staff and wire service reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
CINCINNATI 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Dave Bristol, a former Cincinnati Reds manager who was the Philadelphia 
Phillies' third base coach last season, has been hired as Cincinnati's third 
base coach for 1989, the Reds announced today. 
</P>
<P>
Bristol, 55, who was the Reds' manager from 1966 to 1969, was Philadelphia's 
third base coach until mid-season in 1988, when he was fired along with 
Phillies manager Lee Elia. The Reds said Bristol will be assigned uniform No. 
4, the same number he wore when he managed the Reds. 
</P>
<P>
He will replace Bruce Kimm, who left the Reds in November to become a bench 
coach with the Pittsburgh Pirates. Bristol also managed at Milwaukee (1970-72), 
Atlanta (1976-77) and San Francisco (1979-80), compiling a 658-764 record. 
</P>
<P>
Bristol's new boss, Reds manager Pete Rose, played for Bristol in the major 
leagues and the minor leagues. Bristol was a manager in the Reds' farm system 
for nine years before taking over the Reds in July, 1966, when Don Heffner was 
fired as manager. Bristol guided the Reds to a 39-38 record and a seventh-place 
finish. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA010589-0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 1871 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
January 5, 1989, Thursday, Orange County P.M. Final 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Part A; Page 1; Column 1; Late Final Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
103 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
STATE; 
</P>
<P>
3-YEAR-OLD KILLED IN HOUSE FIRE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A 3-year-old child was trapped by flames and killed today in a fire that swept 
through a house and spread to an adjacent building in the unincorporated Walnut 
Hills area near the City of Industry, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
The fire broke out at the house on Flintgate Drive shortly after 10 a.m., Los 
Angeles County Fire Inspector Chuck Gutierrez said. "The report initially came 
in on 911 that a person was trapped," department spokeswoman Esther Witler 
said. When firefighters arrived, they found the child dead. It was not 
immediately known whether the victim was a boy or girl. There were no other 
reports of injuries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief; Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
